WEBVTT

00:02.080 --> 00:03.878
(RUSTLING)

00:06.360 --> 00:08.351
LOU: This is a true story.

00:18.000 --> 00:21.311
The events depicted
took place in Minnesota,

00:21.400 --> 00:24.791
North and South Dakota
in 1979.

00:36.320 --> 00:37.913
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

00:42.760 --> 00:44.558
At the request
of the survivors,

00:44.640 --> 00:45.914
the names have
been changed.

00:46.400 --> 00:47.799
(FLUTTERING)

01:06.000 --> 01:08.230
Out of respect
for the dead...

01:12.560 --> 01:15.632
The rest has been told
exactly as it occurred.

01:26.160 --> 01:27.309
(GASPS)

01:41.280 --> 01:43.271
NOREEN: Feeling better then?

01:46.000 --> 01:47.195
Mmm.

01:48.240 --> 01:52.598
Doc says you had a reaction
to those pills they gave you.

01:53.480 --> 01:56.950
I told him they were
supposed to kill the cancer,

01:57.040 --> 02:01.034
but he says the pills
may Kill you first.

02:02.080 --> 02:03.275
Hmm?

02:05.200 --> 02:07.157
Is Lou back?

02:07.240 --> 02:10.232
No, and no word either.

02:14.000 --> 02:15.399
Something to eat?

02:15.480 --> 02:16.879
Oh, God, no.

02:18.480 --> 02:19.675
My dad?

02:20.040 --> 02:21.553
Same. No word.

02:23.880 --> 02:25.234
And Molly?

02:26.400 --> 02:29.438
Tried to put her in her own
bed, but she wouldn't go.

02:29.520 --> 02:31.193
Stubborn.
Yeah.

02:32.720 --> 02:34.916
She gets that
from her dad.

02:39.360 --> 02:40.839
(GRUNTS)

02:42.400 --> 02:43.674
(GASPS)

02:44.400 --> 02:47.233
If you're not gonna eat,
Doc says sleep.

02:47.760 --> 02:49.478
Get your strength back.

02:49.920 --> 02:50.910
Hmm.

02:51.000 --> 02:54.391
So, you stay
lying down, you.

02:55.720 --> 02:59.076
And it's okay,
I'll be right here.

03:12.360 --> 03:15.478
BETSY: That night,
I had a dream.

03:16.120 --> 03:19.033
Next week, we'll discuss
economic concepts...

03:19.120 --> 03:21.430
It felt so real

03:21.800 --> 03:24.394
even though I knew
it couldn't be,

03:24.760 --> 03:26.751
or wasn't yet.

03:27.280 --> 03:28.793
TEACHER: Yes, Molly.

03:30.520 --> 03:31.954
(BEEPING)

03:33.320 --> 03:38.474
I dreamt of a magical future,
filled with wondrous devices.

03:40.080 --> 03:42.879
Where everything
you could ever want

03:42.960 --> 03:45.759
would be available
in one amazing place.

03:49.480 --> 03:50.993
All right.
(CLEARS THROAT)

03:53.480 --> 03:55.039
Hey. Mmm-hmm.
Daddy.

03:56.320 --> 03:57.549
(SHUTTER CLICKING)

03:57.640 --> 04:00.200
Just one more. BETSY: And
there was happiness there.

04:09.480 --> 04:11.391
But then I saw
farther still.

04:12.320 --> 04:15.517
Years,
decades into the future.

04:18.160 --> 04:23.189
I saw a handsome older man,
his back still straight.

04:24.680 --> 04:27.877
Visited by his children
and grandchildren.

04:29.280 --> 04:34.400
People of accomplishment,
of contentment.

04:36.440 --> 04:37.953
But then,

04:38.720 --> 04:41.633
I saw chaos.

04:43.800 --> 04:47.077
The fracture of peace
and enlightenment.

04:49.680 --> 04:53.071
And I worried,
that the future I had seen,

04:54.040 --> 04:57.158
magical and
filled with light...

05:01.680 --> 05:03.830
Yeah.
...might never come to pass.

05:07.680 --> 05:09.796
(SIGHS)

05:10.640 --> 05:11.675
I can make it.

05:12.040 --> 05:13.792
(SIRENS BLARING
IN THE DISTANCE)

05:13.880 --> 05:15.234
(SIGHS)

05:15.680 --> 05:16.715
Dinner Sunday?

05:17.680 --> 05:21.435
(CHUCKLES) I'll be there.
In a suit of armor.

05:45.640 --> 05:46.710
Hey!

05:47.760 --> 05:50.274
Hey, hey!
Hey, hey, mister!

05:50.400 --> 05:51.549
(TIRES SCREECH)

05:53.120 --> 05:54.190
What's the trouble,
young fella?

05:54.720 --> 05:56.233
(GLASS SHATTERS)
Mister, we need a ride.

06:06.560 --> 06:07.550
(GUNSHOT)

06:09.440 --> 06:10.714
Come on.

07:00.080 --> 07:02.117
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

07:24.200 --> 07:25.873
People of Earth.

07:28.600 --> 07:30.113
I'm home.

07:38.120 --> 07:39.349
(DOOR CREAKING)

08:35.240 --> 08:36.230
(CLATTERS)

08:36.799 --> 08:38.518
PEGGY: (PANTING)
Come on, Ed.

08:38.600 --> 08:41.352
Come on. Come on.

08:41.440 --> 08:42.999
Come on,
you're gonna be okay.

08:43.080 --> 08:45.196
Just a little further.
Look.

08:47.000 --> 08:48.195
Come on.

08:49.760 --> 08:50.795
(BELL DINGS)

08:51.560 --> 08:53.039
PEGGY: Get outta here.

08:53.120 --> 08:54.155
Sweet Christmas.

08:54.240 --> 08:57.437
Get outta here! Go on, get outta
here! There's a bad man coming!

09:16.960 --> 09:17.950
(GUNSHOT)
(GLASS SHATTERS)

09:18.640 --> 09:19.914
(DOGS BARKING
IN THE DISTANCE)

09:20.240 --> 09:22.959
Okay, I'm gonna use the
phone. I'm gonna call...

09:23.760 --> 09:26.354
Hon, come on.
Let's go, come on.

09:37.120 --> 09:38.679
Come on.

09:40.400 --> 09:41.799
(THUDS)

09:56.640 --> 09:58.517
Oh! Don't! Don't!

09:59.080 --> 10:01.356
You were supposed to
watch them, Ed and Peggy.

10:04.560 --> 10:05.630
Come on.

10:08.240 --> 10:11.198
(GRUNTING)

10:11.360 --> 10:12.714
(DOOR CREAKING)

10:15.040 --> 10:16.269
ED: Yeah. Okay.

10:16.360 --> 10:17.589
I don't know, Ed.

10:17.720 --> 10:19.040
It's okay.
(MUMBLING)

10:19.880 --> 10:21.473
We can lock it
from the inside.

10:21.560 --> 10:24.837
Hide out till they're...
Till we're rescued.

10:27.760 --> 10:30.513
World War lll out there
in case you didn't notice.

10:30.600 --> 10:32.830
You okay there?
Don't start.

10:33.360 --> 10:36.796
She blindsided me, okay?
A pack of wolves at the door.

10:36.880 --> 10:38.632
I didn't think
the bitch...

10:38.720 --> 10:41.030
Didn't think she'd be
dumb enough to sucker me.

10:44.080 --> 10:47.596
Only one way he could
have gone, Hanzee. Huh?

10:47.680 --> 10:50.718
And your feeling is we go the
same way, instead of home to bed.

10:50.800 --> 10:53.235
Yeah. In a hurry.

10:53.720 --> 10:55.677
(BOTH PANTING)

10:56.640 --> 10:59.632
FUBAR, yeah?
FUBAR.

11:16.600 --> 11:18.273
We got to lock it.

11:19.400 --> 11:20.549
Here.

11:22.800 --> 11:24.279
(CLATTERING)

11:28.280 --> 11:30.271
Come on, come on.

11:33.560 --> 11:34.675
Here.

11:37.080 --> 11:41.836
Sit down. You can do it.
Come on. You sit here.

11:41.960 --> 11:43.633
(BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY)

11:45.920 --> 11:47.240
Come here.

11:48.640 --> 11:51.632
Sorry. I gotta...

11:53.640 --> 11:55.278
It's bad.

11:55.400 --> 11:59.314
Hold on. Let me just see
how bad it is.

12:03.360 --> 12:04.634
(GRUNTS)

12:05.680 --> 12:06.715
Okay.

12:08.200 --> 12:09.952
You're gonna be okay.

12:17.000 --> 12:19.640
Peggy, I don't think
we're gonna make it.

12:20.200 --> 12:21.429
(SCOFFS)

12:21.520 --> 12:23.750
Don't you say that,
Ed Blumquist.

12:23.840 --> 12:25.831
We've come this far.
We're gonna go all the way.

12:25.920 --> 12:28.833
No, I'm saying even
if we get out of this,

12:28.920 --> 12:32.197
I don't think we're gonna
make it, you and me.

12:35.040 --> 12:37.509
What are you saying?
We're just too different.

12:37.960 --> 12:42.431
Don't say that.
This, what we been through...

12:42.520 --> 12:46.195
Adversity, that's what
seals the bond.

12:46.280 --> 12:47.918
Makes us stronger.

12:48.000 --> 12:50.071
(STUTTERS) Like
how a bone heals. Peg...

12:50.680 --> 12:51.670
Peg...

12:51.760 --> 12:55.833
No. No, I know I had my
doubts. I know, but I'm sure now.

12:55.960 --> 12:59.032
Peg. Will you just
let me talk? I'm sure.

13:01.240 --> 13:04.232
You're always trying
to fix everything,

13:04.320 --> 13:07.358
but sometimes
nothing's broken.

13:09.280 --> 13:11.635
Everything's
working just fine.

13:13.680 --> 13:16.638
If you can't see that,
if you don't know that...

13:16.720 --> 13:17.790
Ed.

13:17.880 --> 13:19.234
I love you.

13:20.760 --> 13:21.795
I do.

13:26.920 --> 13:30.390
All I'm ever gonna want
is to get back to what we had.

13:53.760 --> 13:55.080
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

14:23.520 --> 14:24.510
Hello.

14:30.120 --> 14:31.394
(GUN COCKS)

14:31.480 --> 14:34.950
Gale, be reasonable.

15:02.320 --> 15:03.993
From this moment forward,

15:04.600 --> 15:09.276
I decree, no more
schnitzel or strudel.

15:11.240 --> 15:13.800
Let's get some
American food up in...

15:18.840 --> 15:19.989
(WHISTLES)

15:27.160 --> 15:28.878
(HORSES NEIGHING
IN THE DISTANCE)

16:01.760 --> 16:03.159
(DOOR CREAKS)

16:12.640 --> 16:14.039
(EXHALES)

16:24.520 --> 16:26.557
Everyone's dead.

16:26.720 --> 16:28.154
(CHUCKLES)

16:29.960 --> 16:31.917
(CLATTERING)

16:40.440 --> 16:41.669
(CLEARS THROAT)

16:48.080 --> 16:49.718
Forget something?

16:50.760 --> 16:53.434
Well, you caught me.

16:54.080 --> 16:55.673
I thought nobody was home.

16:56.360 --> 16:57.589
We're here.

16:57.680 --> 16:59.512
Remind me which one
you are again?

17:00.120 --> 17:01.713
The kid Otto
had with the maid?

17:01.920 --> 17:03.957
You see the shotgun, right?

17:04.160 --> 17:05.752
What, you couldn't
afford a real one?

17:05.839 --> 17:07.911
Times are tough,
friend-o.

17:08.480 --> 17:11.472
Hey, why do you think
I'm stealing the silver?

17:14.280 --> 17:15.759
(CHUCKLES)

17:15.839 --> 17:18.275
Hey, maybe

17:20.640 --> 17:24.270
in the spirit
of human struggle,

17:26.119 --> 17:27.758
we say bygones.

17:28.280 --> 17:31.318
You let me get back in my car
and drive away.

17:32.520 --> 17:35.319
Do you know what the definition
of the word "sovereignty" is?

17:35.640 --> 17:36.994
What am I,

17:37.240 --> 17:39.959
Professor from Gilligan's
Island? (CHUCKLES)

17:40.240 --> 17:43.596
Sovereignty is absolute
power and authority.

17:45.320 --> 17:47.789
Like a king?
Exactly.

17:49.720 --> 17:51.313
Which is who I am.

17:52.680 --> 17:54.239
Your king.

17:54.760 --> 17:56.114
Uh...

17:57.480 --> 17:59.312
It's America, brother.

18:00.080 --> 18:01.753
We don't do kings.

18:02.280 --> 18:03.839
Oh, we do.

18:04.680 --> 18:06.159
We do.

18:07.760 --> 18:10.229
We just call them
something else.

18:12.720 --> 18:15.314
See, today is my
coronation day.

18:17.440 --> 18:20.353
And on coronation day,
I've always believed,

18:21.280 --> 18:25.911
a new king should start his
reign with an act of kindness.

18:26.800 --> 18:28.074
Right on.

18:28.440 --> 18:29.953
And an act of cruelty.

18:32.120 --> 18:35.397
That way, your subjects know
that you're capable of both.

18:36.240 --> 18:37.355
God and monster.

18:37.720 --> 18:38.869
Shit.

18:39.720 --> 18:41.711
Sign me up
for the first one.

18:44.880 --> 18:47.793
Problem is,
Wilma works in the kitchen.

18:47.880 --> 18:49.359
Oh, the Injun?

18:50.040 --> 18:51.030
MIKE: Right.

18:52.200 --> 18:54.840
She has already
received my kindness,

18:54.920 --> 18:56.593
to wit, a brand new car,

18:57.520 --> 19:00.751
and all the money that was in
that cabinet you were searching.

19:02.880 --> 19:04.279
Damn.

19:05.640 --> 19:07.597
Which means you...
Don't tell me.

19:08.240 --> 19:09.719
...are shit out of luck.

19:09.800 --> 19:11.234
(RICKY CHUCKLES)

19:12.160 --> 19:13.389
(SIGHS)

19:16.600 --> 19:17.954
Story of my life,
brother.

19:20.320 --> 19:22.197
Hey, you ever
been to Baltimore?

19:25.360 --> 19:26.350
(GUNSHOT)

19:30.320 --> 19:31.754
(COUGHING)
(RELOADS)

19:34.600 --> 19:36.159
MIKE: An act of cruelty,
remember?

19:40.480 --> 19:41.754
(CHOKING)

19:45.400 --> 19:48.199
Well, I'm bushed, think
I'm gonna go take a nap.

19:49.280 --> 19:51.556
You should get
some rest, too.

19:52.960 --> 19:56.032
For in the morning, we journey
home to bathe in that warm champagne

19:56.120 --> 19:58.430
that is
corporate praise.

20:01.800 --> 20:03.234
Who knows?

20:04.160 --> 20:06.356
Maybe they'll even
throw us a parade.

20:11.160 --> 20:12.719
I love a parade.

20:42.800 --> 20:44.791
(GRUNTS)
Ed, save your strength, huh?

20:44.880 --> 20:47.156
You're gonna be fine and
we'll figure this all out.

20:48.400 --> 20:50.994
And I know I've been
nothing but trouble to you.

20:51.080 --> 20:52.229
I know.

20:52.320 --> 20:53.390
(DOOR CLATTERS)

20:56.760 --> 20:58.353
(RATTLING)

21:00.520 --> 21:02.511
(WHISPERS) Maybe he just
walks away.

21:02.880 --> 21:04.553
(RATTLING CONTINUES)

21:21.920 --> 21:23.911
He's trying to
smoke us out!

21:25.680 --> 21:26.875
(COUGHS)

21:31.400 --> 21:32.913
Help me, Ed.

21:34.400 --> 21:37.631
They'll see... Somebody...
They'll see and they'll...

21:38.200 --> 21:39.474
They'll call someone.

21:40.600 --> 21:42.034
They'll see.

21:45.400 --> 21:47.835
Oh, my God, Ed.

21:48.560 --> 21:50.551
It's just like the movie.

21:51.400 --> 21:54.233
The movie I was
watching this morning.

21:54.640 --> 21:56.153
With the guy
all tied up.

21:56.240 --> 21:58.709
The Gerhardi,
on the TV.

21:58.800 --> 22:01.360
There was this...
There was this couple.

22:01.440 --> 22:05.354
This French...
And they were on the run.

22:07.080 --> 22:09.230
From the Nazi...

22:09.360 --> 22:10.873
(STUTTERING)

22:12.240 --> 22:15.312
And the husband,
or whatever he was,

22:15.400 --> 22:17.994
he got shot,
just like you.

22:19.920 --> 22:22.673
But then they
hid out in this...

22:22.760 --> 22:26.037
Well, it wasn't a supermarket,
it was a farmhouse,

22:26.120 --> 22:28.509
but they hid out,

22:28.600 --> 22:32.434
and the Nazi tried to
smoke 'em out. Just like this.

22:33.080 --> 22:34.434
But they got out!

22:35.120 --> 22:36.474
Ed, they got out.

22:36.560 --> 22:37.789
They were saved!

22:37.960 --> 22:39.359
(FIRE RUSTLING)

22:47.320 --> 22:48.640
Ed.

22:50.720 --> 22:52.916
Ed? Ed!

22:53.000 --> 22:54.559
No! Ed?

22:54.640 --> 22:55.994
Ed!

22:57.280 --> 22:58.918
No. (CRYING)

23:02.920 --> 23:04.433
(RATTLING)

23:07.600 --> 23:08.920
(COUGHING)

23:10.920 --> 23:12.433
(GRUNTING)

23:38.920 --> 23:40.593
Peggy! It's okay.
It's okay.

23:40.680 --> 23:41.636
It's me. It's me.
Where is he?

23:41.720 --> 23:42.835
Where is he?
It's okay.

23:42.920 --> 23:44.149
I'll Kill him!
No, no, no. He's gone.

23:44.240 --> 23:45.674
No, you're lying to me!
He's gone.

23:45.760 --> 23:48.354
Put this down!
No, no! You stay back!

23:48.440 --> 23:49.794
Where is he?
Where is the Indian?

23:49.880 --> 23:52.520
Where is he? He tried
to smoke us out! Stop.

23:52.600 --> 23:54.159
Just like in the movie!
Peggy, there's no smoke!

23:54.240 --> 23:55.913
No! No.
There's no smoke.

23:56.000 --> 23:58.116
We need to check on Ed.
He's shot. He's shot!

23:58.200 --> 24:01.511
He's shot and the Indian,
where is he?

24:01.600 --> 24:04.194
He tried to light a fire,
just like in the movie!

24:04.280 --> 24:05.270
Just like in the movie!

24:05.360 --> 24:06.350
(PANTING)
Where is he?

24:07.040 --> 24:08.553
(SIGHS)

24:08.640 --> 24:09.835
Peggy.
Where's the Indian?

24:09.920 --> 24:11.752
Just look at me.
Okay...

24:11.840 --> 24:14.150
He lit a fire. No, the
Indian got away, okay?

24:14.240 --> 24:16.675
We followed Ed's
blood trail, okay?

24:16.760 --> 24:17.830
Kicked in the door. Us.

24:17.960 --> 24:19.439
No, he's here. The Indian
was never in the building.

24:19.560 --> 24:20.709
No. He was.

24:20.800 --> 24:22.552
Ed'll tell you. Ed.

24:22.640 --> 24:24.551
Ed! Ed!

24:24.640 --> 24:26.472
Come on, Ed, we're saved.

24:27.000 --> 24:28.479
Ed, they're here!

24:28.560 --> 24:30.278
We're rescued. Ed!

24:30.680 --> 24:33.399
(CRYING) Ed? Ed!

24:35.040 --> 24:36.678
Come on, Ed.

24:51.880 --> 24:54.394
There's a manhunt
underway for our man.

24:55.000 --> 24:56.195
He won't get far.

24:57.880 --> 25:00.838
Local PD says your
father-in-law's in the ICU.

25:02.400 --> 25:05.438
"Cautiously optimistic"
is the report.

25:06.680 --> 25:08.034
What about your boss?

25:13.280 --> 25:14.315
(SCHMIDT CHUCKLES)

25:14.720 --> 25:18.759
(STUTTERS) I don't even know
how to write this thing up.

25:20.160 --> 25:21.559
Where to begin.

25:23.120 --> 25:24.679
Well, like anything,
I guess.

25:24.760 --> 25:29.630
You know, start at the start
and work your way to the end.

25:33.840 --> 25:35.035
Okay, then.

25:37.440 --> 25:39.192
You're gonna be okay.

25:44.960 --> 25:48.271
I'm gonna take Peggy Blumquist
back to Minnesota.

25:48.400 --> 25:50.391
Anyone's got a problem
with that...

25:51.120 --> 25:54.636
Well, after the week I've had,
they can keep it to themselves.

26:19.320 --> 26:20.674
Mmm.

26:22.840 --> 26:23.989
Morning.

26:26.920 --> 26:29.230
Is Lou back?
No.

26:30.200 --> 26:31.713
So...

26:32.720 --> 26:34.199
Is it...

26:37.240 --> 26:38.469
Do you feel it?

26:39.520 --> 26:40.954
Feel what?

26:42.160 --> 26:45.676
My aunt lost her
bosom to cancer.

26:46.720 --> 26:52.033
Said it felt like somebody took a
hot poker and put it through her heart.

26:54.880 --> 26:57.394
No. Not like that.

26:59.040 --> 27:00.314
Not yet.

27:02.920 --> 27:06.276
You know how sometimes you get a
peach from the bowl and one side is

27:06.360 --> 27:09.352
ripe and yellow, and the
other is black and moldy?

27:13.240 --> 27:16.596
That's the only way
I can think to describe it.

27:17.960 --> 27:22.318
Camus says knowing we're
gonna die makes life absurd.

27:24.280 --> 27:26.078
Well, I don't know
who that is,

27:27.200 --> 27:29.999
but I'm guessing he doesn't
have a six-year-old girl.

27:31.200 --> 27:32.520
He's French.

27:32.600 --> 27:34.193
I don't care if
he's from Mars.

27:34.280 --> 27:36.954
Nobody with any sense would
say something that foolish.

27:38.800 --> 27:42.236
We're put on this Earth
to do a job,

27:43.560 --> 27:47.269
and each of us gets
the time we get to do it.

27:50.760 --> 27:52.671
(CHUCKLES) And when
this life is over

27:53.600 --> 27:56.069
and you stand
in front of the Lord...

27:59.640 --> 28:02.837
Well, you try telling Him it
was all some Frenchman's joke.

28:05.120 --> 28:06.599
Do you think...

28:08.440 --> 28:12.957
Is there any chance
I could be tried federal?

28:15.440 --> 28:16.714
Why?

28:17.680 --> 28:22.390
I thought, well, maybe I could
serve my time in California.

28:22.480 --> 28:25.359
There was this news
report on the TV

28:25.440 --> 28:27.716
about how there's
this penitentiary

28:27.800 --> 28:32.033
just north of San Francisco
that looks out on the bay?

28:32.120 --> 28:33.793
Doesn't that sound nice?

28:34.800 --> 28:36.598
Maybe see a pelican.

28:39.200 --> 28:41.237
We'll see what we can do.

28:48.120 --> 28:50.794
I was there at the end,
you know.

28:50.880 --> 28:53.315
After the war,
when Saigon fell.

28:54.000 --> 28:57.231
On the USS Kirk, (SIGHS)
patrolling the coast.

28:57.480 --> 28:59.232
And when the country went,
it went fast.

28:59.320 --> 29:02.472
And we had, like, you know,
24 hours to get everybody out.

29:03.280 --> 29:08.673
But not just Americans, but
our allies, the South Vietnamese.

29:09.720 --> 29:12.712
All packed onto
boats and helicopters.

29:14.160 --> 29:17.869
We stood on the deck
and waved them in.

29:19.440 --> 29:21.192
One by one,
they'd land, unload,

29:21.320 --> 29:25.279
and then we'd push
the whirlybirds into the sea.

29:25.360 --> 29:26.350
Damnedest thing.

29:27.200 --> 29:30.750
But then this Chinook comes,
and those things...

29:30.840 --> 29:34.515
Well, you just can't land one
on a ship this size.

29:35.560 --> 29:36.675
So we wave him off.

29:37.680 --> 29:40.638
But the pilot's got
his whole family inside,

29:40.720 --> 29:43.997
and he's running out of fuel,
so it's now or never.

29:46.360 --> 29:48.715
So he hovers
over the deck.

29:50.240 --> 29:53.392
People start jumping,

29:55.920 --> 29:58.116
scared or not,
onto the ship.

30:04.320 --> 30:06.311
There was a baby.

30:07.720 --> 30:10.234
Literally,
a tiny baby.

30:12.080 --> 30:13.718
And the mother just...

30:14.200 --> 30:15.759
Just drops him.

30:18.360 --> 30:20.158
And one of my boys...

30:21.320 --> 30:23.231
Like catching a ball...

30:23.840 --> 30:26.150
He just sticks out
his hands...

30:30.080 --> 30:31.991
So, now,
everybody's out,

30:32.080 --> 30:35.550
and I'm thinking how the heck is this
pilot, right, how's he gonna get out?

30:35.640 --> 30:38.154
But he maneuvers
off the port bow

30:38.240 --> 30:40.959
and he hovers there
for the longest time doing,

30:41.040 --> 30:42.917
you know,
what we learn later,

30:43.360 --> 30:45.510
uh, taking off
his flight suit.

30:47.040 --> 30:49.350
And somehow he rolls
the bird on its side,

30:49.440 --> 30:52.319
and just before it
hits the water, he jumps.

30:53.440 --> 30:55.795
Six thousand pounds,

30:55.880 --> 30:59.077
angry helicopter parts
flying all around him.

31:01.800 --> 31:03.837
(CHUCKLES) And somehow
he makes it.

31:06.360 --> 31:08.112
How'd he do that?

31:14.600 --> 31:16.398
What are you saying?

31:19.400 --> 31:20.799
Your husband.

31:21.720 --> 31:25.190
He said he was gonna protect
his family no matter what,

31:25.920 --> 31:27.957
and I acted like
I didn't understand,

31:29.480 --> 31:30.754
but I do.

31:33.280 --> 31:36.910
It's the rock
we all push, men.

31:39.240 --> 31:41.436
We call it
our burden, but...

31:42.480 --> 31:44.517
It's really our privilege.

31:50.400 --> 31:53.392
I never meant for
any of this to happen.

31:55.040 --> 31:56.269
You know?

31:59.680 --> 32:01.000
Not to Ed.

32:01.800 --> 32:03.313
Not to anybody.

32:05.880 --> 32:07.678
I just wanted
to be someone.

32:08.400 --> 32:10.391
Well, you're
somebody now.

32:13.400 --> 32:14.959
No. See,

32:16.280 --> 32:18.032
I wanted to choose.

32:18.840 --> 32:20.399
Be my own me.

32:20.480 --> 32:23.472
Not be defined by
someone else's expectations...

32:24.640 --> 32:27.598
And then that guy...
That stupid guy!

32:27.680 --> 32:29.557
Walked out into the...

32:31.000 --> 32:33.037
Why did he
have to do that?

32:34.480 --> 32:36.118
You mean the victim?

32:37.880 --> 32:39.917
No. That's not fair.

32:41.280 --> 32:43.271
'Cause I'm a victim, too.

32:44.200 --> 32:46.111
Was a victim first.

32:46.200 --> 32:48.396
Before him.
Victim of what?

32:50.480 --> 32:51.800
Well, it's...

32:52.440 --> 32:54.909
You wouldn't understand,
you're a man.

32:58.400 --> 33:00.073
It's a lie, okay?

33:01.280 --> 33:03.271
That you can do it all.

33:03.360 --> 33:07.399
Be a wife, and a mother, and
this self-made career woman...

33:07.480 --> 33:09.835
Like there's
37 hours in a day.

33:10.560 --> 33:13.200
And then, when you can't,
they say it's you.

33:13.280 --> 33:14.839
You're faulty.

33:14.920 --> 33:16.115
Like...

33:16.800 --> 33:18.074
Like...

33:19.240 --> 33:21.311
Like you are
inferior somehow.

33:22.440 --> 33:27.150
And then, like, if you could
just get your act together

33:27.760 --> 33:28.989
until you're
half-mad with...

33:29.080 --> 33:30.832
People are dead, Peggy.

